    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Bustos Powers Americans to Victory</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <byline class="print_byline">By John Shaw</byline>
      <byline class="normalized_byline">Shaw, John</byline>
      <abstract>
        <p>United States defeats Cuba, 3-0, in softball at Sydney Olympics (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>Crystl Bustos homered twice as the United States defeated Cuba, 3-0, today to extend its winning streak to 112 games.</p>
        <p>Bustos and Sheila Douty hit successive home runs in the second inning, and Bustos homered again in the fourth for the United States (2-0). Danielle Henderson struck out seven in five-plus innings before Christa Williams recorded the final six outs. Cuba (0-2) had just two hits and a walk off Henderson.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>Crystl Bustos homered twice as the United States defeated Cuba, 3-0, today to extend its winning streak to 112 games.</p>
        <p>Bustos and Sheila Douty hit successive home runs in the second inning, and Bustos homered again in the fourth for the United States (2-0). Danielle Henderson struck out seven in five-plus innings before Christa Williams recorded the final six outs. Cuba (0-2) had just two hits and a walk off Henderson.</p>
        <p>The Americans' last loss was to Australia, 1-0, in a 10-inning game in the world championships in Japan in 1998.</p>
        <p>The Australian team, which uses the memory of that victory over the United States as Olympic inspiration, markets itself as ''Aussie thunder.'' But the Australians started quietly yesterday, snatching a 3-2 victory over lowly New Zealand with a home run in the 10th inning. Still, Australia is considered the only team with a chance to stop the Americans.</p>
        <p>John Shaw</p>
        <p>SYDNEY 2000: SOFTBALL</p>
      </block>
